    "summary": "The Warsaw Pact, formally the Treaty of Friendship, Cooperation and Mutual Assistance, was signed on May 14, 1955, by the Soviet Union and seven Eastern European satellite states: Albania, Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, East Germany, Hungary, Poland, and Romania. The treaty created a formal military alliance with integrated command structures under Soviet leadership, and was explicitly formed in response to West Germany's rearmament and admission to NATO.\n\nIn practice, the Warsaw Pact served as the institutional framework for Soviet military dominance over Eastern Europe. Its structures enabled the Soviet Union to station troops in member countries and justified interventions to suppress political dissent. The Pact was invoked to legitimize the 1956 intervention in Hungary and the 1968 invasion of Czechoslovakia during the [[event:3351|Prague Spring]], though neither action was formally authorized under the treaty's mutual defense provisions.\n\nThe alliance began to fracture as communist regimes collapsed across Eastern Europe in 1989 and 1990. Czechoslovakia, Hungary, and Poland withdrew from the military structure in 1990, and the organization was formally dissolved on July 1, 1991. The collapse of the Warsaw Pact marked the end of the Soviet-dominated security order in Eastern Europe and opened the question of NATO expansion that would dominate European security debates for decades. Several former Warsaw Pact members subsequently joined NATO.",
